Type of Appt:	New

Many thanks for referring this 44-year old lady to clinic.  She was accompanied by her mother.  In total she describes a 2-year history of alteration in her bowel habit that has worsened over the last 4 months, but over the last week has improved.  She describes generalised abdominal pain with cramping exacerbations.  She feels urgency with the pain, but there is no relief with defaecation.  Her bowels have been moving between 1-7 times in 24 hours, and have tended to alternate between feeling constipated and passing diarrhoea.

Over the last 4 months she has noticed fresh red bleeding on the toilet paper on wiping and in the toilet pan also mixed with stools with every bowel motion.  She has also noticed mucus per rectum.  The bleeding and mucus has resolved over the last week.

Past medical history:

Factor V deficiency
Thalassaemia trait
Anaemia
Hypothyroidism

Drug history:

No known drug allergies
125mcg Levothyroxine







Social history:

Non-smoker, alcohol - one drink at the weekend.  She is currently a nursing student and lives with her parents.  Her maternal grandfather has Crohn's disease, a paternal cousin has bowel problems.

On examination today Test Patient weighed 55.4 kgs and appeared thin.  Her abdomen was soft and non-tender with no organomegaly and normal bowel sounds.

Test Patient clearly needs investigation and may well have inflammatory bowel disease.  I have organised a series of routine bloods tests, including full blood count, U and E's, LFT's, CRP and haeamatinics.  She will have a colonoscopy and we will see her in clinic with her results.

Many thanks.

Yours sincerely




Dr A Conlin
